<!--
  wazuh-home (manager): logall_json setting.

  Add this single line inside the existing <global> block in
  /var/ossec/etc/ossec.conf on the manager VM. Example resulting block:

      <global>
        <jsonout_output>yes</jsonout_output>
        <alerts_log>yes</alerts_log>
        <logall_json>yes</logall_json>     <-- this is the addition
        <email_notification>no</email_notification>
        ...
      </global>

  Why: Wazuh's default behaviour writes only ALERTS (level >=3) to
  alerts.json. Everything decoded at level 0 (e.g. the catch-all DNS
  rule 100250 in manager-rules.xml) is silently dropped after decoding.

  logall_json:yes makes the manager additionally write every decoded
  event to /var/ossec/logs/archives/archives.json regardless of level.
  That's how the Vault VM DNS event stream becomes searchable:
    - rule 100250 (level 0): visible in archives.json, not alerts.json
    - rule 100251 (level 3, resolved): visible in both
    - rule 100252 (level 6, blocked):  visible in both

  Trade-off: archives.json grows fast (one line per decoded event).
  Wazuh's default logrotate config under /etc/logrotate.d/wazuh
  handles this, but worth checking disk usage with
      du -sh /var/ossec/logs/archives/
  after a few days.

  After editing, restart the manager:
      sudo systemctl restart wazuh-manager
-->

<logall_json>yes</logall_json>
